"# Appendix G — TUI cheat-sheet

Quick reference for the TUI renderer's conventions. Cell characters, header layout, palette strip, and how to invoke the render verb.

## The verb

```
(composer/render-tui canvas [opts]) -> string
```

- `canvas` — a canvas record.
- `opts` — optional plist of rendering options.

Options:

- `:brand #f` — suppress the brand header (three stripes + title).
- `:palette 'html-16` — force the palette strip.
- `:color #f` — disable ANSI color escape codes (currently the TUI does not emit escapes anyway; this option is for forward-compatibility).

## The brand header

```
[pink ] ========================================
[green] ========================================
[brown] ========================================

MOTOI COMPOSER — canvas <bind-label>
----------------------------------------
```

Three lines of stripe rules labeled by color. Blank line. Title line with the canvas's bind label. Dash rule separator.

`bind-label` is a slash-joined string of the canvas's bind path. `(cart/main)` renders as `cart/main`. Multi-level binds render as `cart/main/synth`.

## Widget renderings (compact reference)

Slider:

```
[==========|---------] <label> <value>
```

Button:

```
[ <label> ]
```

Toggle:

```
[X] <label>       ;; on
[ ] <label>       ;; off
```

Text-field:

```
<label>: \"<value>\"
```

Color-picker:

```
color(<bind>): <name-or-hex>
```

ADSR:

```
ADSR: a=<a> d=<d> s=<s> r=<r>
```

Instrument-picker:

```
instrument: [<choice1>|<choice2>|...] chosen=<chosen>
```

Piano-roll:

```
piano-roll: <bind> (<n-notes> notes, <n-steps> steps)
   B ................
  A# ................
  ...
   C #...............
```

Sprite-grid:

```
sprite: <bind> (<w>x<h>, palette <palette>)
  <row of chars>
  <row of chars>
  ...
```

Tile-map:

```
tile-map: (<cols>x<rows>)
  <row of chars>
  ...
```

Timeline:

```
timeline: entities=<csv> duration=<d>s fps=<fps> frames=<n>
```

fx-chain:

```
fx-chain: <fx1> -> <fx2> -> <fx3>
```

Empty fx-chain:

```
fx-chain: (empty)
```

Live-code:

```
live-code: \"<preview>\"
```

Voice-pool (v1.1):

```
voice-pool: 16 voices, steal=<policy>
   1 <instrument-name-or-(free)>
   2 <instrument-name-or-(free)>
   ...
  15 <instrument-name-or-(free)>
  16 [MIX] <- #<v1>,#<v2>,...
```

## Cell character mapping

Palette-indexed cells (sprite-grid, tile-map, piano-roll character rows) use:

- `.` for index 0.
- `1`, `2`, ..., `9` for indices 1-9.
- `a`, `b`, `c`, `d`, `e`, `f` for indices 10-15.
- `?` for any other value.

Piano-roll cells use `#` for a placed note and `.` for empty.

## The palette strip (if html-16 is used)

Appended below the widgets:

```
palette (html-16):
  01:black  02:white  03:crimson  04:forestgreen  05:peachpuff  06:gold  07:coral  08:plum  09:teal  10:sienna  11:pink  12:skyblue  13:khaki  14:lavender  15:mediumseagreen  16:saddlebrown
```

The strip is triggered when any widget in the canvas has `:palette 'html-16` set, or when the caller passes `:palette 'html-16` to `composer/render-tui`.

## The tree logo

```
     /\\
    /  \\
   /----\\
  /      \\
 /--------\\
     ||
     ||
```

Returned by `(composer/tree-logo)`. Print it as a landing header:

```scheme
(display (composer/tree-logo))
(newline)
```

## Keyboard conventions (proposed)

The TUI renderer itself is a pure function producing a string. A CURSES-STYLE INTERACTIVE driver on top of the renderer would map keys to widget interactions. The proposed conventions (per the v1.1 spec) are:

- Arrow keys navigate between widgets.
- Enter activates a button, opens a numeric-entry sheet on a slider, toggles a toggle.
- Left / Right arrow on a slider steps by `:step`.
- Home / End on a slider jump to min / max.
- Digit keys 1-9 select tools in a sprite editor.
- `s` for save, `l` for load, `q` for quit.

The interactive driver is not shipped in v1.1; only the render verb is. Kids running interactively use Curator's canvas rendering. Terminal users use the render string for snapshot inspection and headless testing.

## ANSI escape codes

The v1.1 TUI does not currently emit escape codes; every output is plain text. The renderer includes ANSI helpers in the source (`TUI_ANSI` export in `tui.js`) for future use. If a caller wants colored output, they can wrap widget lines in escapes themselves.

## Redraw model

`composer/render-tui` is pure. Caller decides when to redraw. Typical patterns:

- Snapshot mode: call once, print, done.
- Interactive mode: call on every widget change, diff against previous frame, paint the diff.
- Test mode: call, compare against expected string, assert.

## Line width

Widgets render at approximately 40-cell width by default (see `STRIPE_WIDTH` in `tui.js`). Sliders are 20-cell bars. Sprite/tile grids are as wide as their pixel count plus a 2-space indent.

Terminal narrower than 40 cells will wrap the header stripes but the widget rows will fit as long as your sprite is not too wide.

## Where the code lives

`lib/composer/tui.js`. All widget renderers are pure functions. The main entry point is `renderCanvasToTUI(canvas, opts)`. Named exports include `TREE_LOGO` and `TUI_ANSI`.

## A full example

```scheme
(define c
  (composer/canvas (list :bind '(cart))
    (composer/slider :label \"BPM\" :bind '(cart :bpm) :min 60 :max 240 :step 1 :value 120)
    (composer/toggle :bind '(cart :muted) :label \"Muted\")
    (composer/instrument-picker :bind '(cart :wave)
                                :choices '(sine square triangle saw noise))))

(display (composer/render-tui c))
(newline)
```

Verified output:

```
[pink ] ========================================
[green] ========================================
[brown] ========================================

MOTOI COMPOSER — canvas cart
----------------------------------------
[==========|---------] BPM 120

[ ] Muted

instrument: [sine|square|triangle|saw|noise] chosen=sine
```

## Suppress the brand header

```scheme
(display (composer/render-tui c '(:brand #f)))
```

Renders without the three stripes and the title.

That is the TUI in full. Every widget kind renders. Every canvas renders. The composer follows kids into terminals, into SSH sessions, into CI logs.
")
